<DocsLayout title="ctx_analyze" description="Shannon entropy analysis with strategy recommendation — understand your file's information density and pick the optimal compression mode.">
  <p>
    <code>ctx_analyze</code> performs deep information-theoretic analysis on a file using Shannon entropy
    and Jaccard similarity. It tells you exactly how much real information the file contains
    and recommends the best compression strategy.
  </p>

  <h2>Parameters</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>string</td><td>Yes</td><td>Path to the file to analyze</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Example</h2>
  <pre><code>{`$ ctx_analyze middleware.ts

ANALYSIS: middleware.ts (78L, 1856 tok)

Entropy Distribution:
  H̄ = 3.2 bits/char
  Low-entropy (H<2.0): 14 lines (18%)
  High-entropy (H>4.0): 22 lines (28%)

Strategy Comparison:
  raw                      1856 tok  —
  aggressive               1420 tok  -23%
  signatures (tdd)          312 tok  -83%
  entropy                   298 tok  -84%
  aggressive + §MAP        1380 tok  -26%
  cache hit                  13 tok  -99%

Recommendation: signatures (best first-read savings)`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Understanding the Output</h2>

  <h3>Entropy Distribution</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>H̄ (average entropy)</strong> — bits of information per character. Higher = more unique content.</li>
    <li><strong>Low-entropy lines (H &lt; 2.0)</strong> — boilerplate, imports, closing braces. Safe to remove.</li>
    <li><strong>High-entropy lines (H &gt; 4.0)</strong> — unique logic, algorithms, configuration. Must keep.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Strategy Comparison</h3>
  <p>
    Shows exact tiktoken-measured token counts for each compression strategy.
    The recommendation tells you which mode saves the most tokens on the first read.
  </p>

  <h2>TDD Integration</h2>
  <p>
    When <a href="/docs/tdd">TDD mode</a> is active, the strategy comparison includes additional
    TDD-specific strategies like <code>aggressive + §MAP</code> and uses TDD notation
    for signature counts.
  </p>

  <h2>When to Use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Deciding which <code>ctx_read</code> mode to use for a large file</li>
    <li>Understanding why a file compresses well (or poorly)</li>
    <li>Identifying files with high boilerplate content</li>
    <li>Optimizing token usage for cost-sensitive projects</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
